ce:section.ce:para:
Taken by a Bruker X-ray Diffractometer (D2 Phaser) and monochromatized Cu K radiation (λ = 1.5418 

                              Å

                        ), X-ray diffraction pattern was used to identify the phase of the as-prepared samples. The surface morphology of the as-prepared materials was investigated using a field emission scanning electron microscope (FE-SEM, JSM-6500F, JEOL) and a transmission electron microscope (TEM, FEI Tecnai 20 G2 S-Twin Transmission Electron Microscope). A JASCO 5100 spectrometer was used to perform Raman measurements at room temperature (laser excitation wavelength, 532 nm). Drop-casting was used to deposit thin films of materials on Si wafers, which were then cured in ambient conditions for 24 h. The laser power was kept at 0.1 mW to avoid laser heat generation. The 520 cm−1 peak was utilized to calibrate Raman shifts on a silicon wafer. X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy was carried out to analyze the surface electron states change of the as-prepared materials (XPS, JPS-9030, JEOL). The C 1s (284.6 eV) was used to calibrate the binding energies. Soft-XAS of the C L-edge was recorded at the BL20A1 beamline utilizing the total electron yield (TEY) mode, with a pressure of 5x10−9 torr and a resolving power E/ΔE = 8000, at the National Synchrotron Radiation Research Center (NSRRC) in Taiwan. Athena and Origin software were used to normalize all spectra.
